context: <b8_0>Washington University<b8_0/> has a large number of student-run musical groups on campus, including <a0_0>12<a0_0/> official a cappella groups. <a1_0>The Pikers<a1_0/>, an all-male group, is the oldest such group on campus. <a2_0>The Greenleafs<a2_0/>, an all-female group is the oldest (and only) female group on campus. The Mosaic Whispers, founded in <b6_0>1991<b6_0/>, is the oldest co-ed group on campus. They have produced <b5_0><b7_0>9<b7_0/><b5_0/> albums and have appeared on a number of compilation albums, including Ben Folds' Ben Folds Presents: University A Cappella! The Amateurs, who also appeared on this album, is another co-ed a cappella group on campus, founded in <a3_0>1991<a3_0/>. They have recorded <b9_0>seven<b9_0/> albums and toured extensively. After Dark is a co-ed a cappella group founded in 2001. It has released three albums and has won several Contemporary A Capella Recording (CARA) awards. In <a4_0>2008<a4_0/> the group performed on MSNBC during coverage of the vice presidential debate with specially written songs about Joe Biden and Sarah Palin. The Ghost Lights, founded in 2010, is the campus's newest and only Broadway, Movies, and Television soundtrack group. They have performed multiple philanthropic concerts in the greater St. Louis area and were honored in November 2010 with the opportunity to perform for Nobel Laureate Douglass North at his birthday celebration.
